akistani urban bureaucracy, showing how the material forms of postcolonial bureaucratic documentation produce a distinctive political economy of paper that shapes how the city is constructed, regulated, and inhabited. Files, maps, petitions, and visiting cards constitute the enduring material infrastructure of more ephemeral classifications, laws, and institutional organizations. Matthew S. Hull develops a fresh approach to state governance as a material practice, explaining why writing practices designed during the colonial era to isolate the government from society have become a means of participation in it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBureaucracyzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aBureaucracyzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCapitals (Cities)zPakistanxPlanning. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aCity planningzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aGovernment paperworkzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aGovernment paperworkzPakistanzIslāmābād. 0aMunicipal governmentzPakistanvRecords and correspondence. 0aPublic recordszPakistanzIslāmābād. 70(DE-601)1043124910(DE-588)4139988-2aDokument2gnd 70(DE-601)1061285070(DE-588)4063317-2aVerwaltung2gnd 70(DE-601)1061538110(DE-588)4056754-0aStadtplanung2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  abuilders.  abureaucracy.  abureaucratic documentation.  abureaucrats.  abusinessmen.  acolonial era.  acontemporary history.  aimams.  aislamabad.  alegal anthropology.  amaterial infrastructure.  amaterials.  amiddle east scholars.  amiddle east.  amodern pakistan.  anonfiction.  apakistan.  apaper artifacts.  apaper documents.  apaper mediation.  apolitical economy.  apoliticians.  apostcolonialism.  aproperty owners.  asocial science.  astate government.  aurban bureaucracy.  aurban landscape.